.TH JRNLC 1 "2025-03-15" "jrnl 0.3.0" "User Commands"

.SH NAME
jrnlc \- minimal CLI journaling tool

.SH SYNOPSIS
.B jrnlc
.B init
.RI [ --local | --global]


.B jrnlc
.B add
.RI [ TEXT ] " " [ tag ] " " [ --local | --global ]

.B jrnlc
.B show
.RI [ specifier ] " " [ options ] " " [ --local | --global ]

.B jrnlc
.B backup
.RI [ filename ]

.SH DESCRIPTION
jrnlc is a small command-line journaling tool that stores
journal entries in a plain-text format and provides simple
filtering based on time and ranges.

When adding entries, jrnlc supports implicit tag continuation:
.TP
- If a tag is explicitly provided, it is used.
.TP
- If no tag is provided, the tag from the previous entry is reused.
.TP
- If no previous tag exists, entries default to the tag "jrnl".
.TP
- An explicitly empty tag is treated as invalid and falls back to the same behavior.

This allows fast journaling without repeatedly retyping tags,
while still allowing explicit overrides.

.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BR add " " TEXT " " --tag " " [tag]
Add a new journal entry with an optional tag. If no tag is
provided, the previous entry's tag may be reused.
.RS
Implicit tag continuation:
.TP
- If a tag is provided, it is used.
.TP
- If no tag is provided, the previous entry's tag is reused.
.TP
- If no previous tag exists, defaults to "jrnl".
.RE
.TP
.BR show " " --before " " TIME
Show entries before TIME.

.TP
.BR show " " --after " " TIME
Show entries after TIME.

.TP
.BR show " " :N
Show the first N entries.

.TP
.BR show " " N:
Show the last N entries.

.TP
.BR --local
Operate on the local journal in the current directory.

.TP
.BR --global
Operate on the global journal.

.TP
.B TIME format
YYYY-MM-DD HH:MM

.TP
.BR backup " " [filename]
Create a backup at the path specified in the configuration
file. An optional filename may be provided.

.TP
.BR -h ", " --help
Show help and exit.

.TP
.BR -v ", " --version
Show version information and exit.

.SH FILES
.TP
.I $XDG_DATA_HOME/jrnlc/journal.txt
Default global journal storage file.
If
.I XDG_DATA_HOME
is not set,
.I ~/.local/share/jrnlc/journal.txt
is used instead.

.TP
.I $XDG_DATA_HOME/jrnlc/backup
Default backup directory.
If
.I XDG_DATA_HOME
is not set,
.I ~/.local/share/jrnlc/backup
is used instead.

.TP
.I $XDG_CONFIG_HOME/jrnlc/jrnl.txt
Configuration file.
If
.I XDG_CONFIG_HOME
is not set,
.I ~/.config/jrnlc/jrnl.txt
is used instead.

.SH NOTES
If a local journal is not present, jrnlc falls back to the
global journal unless --local is explicitly specified.

jrnlc is intentionally minimal. Each invocation performs a
single operation, following traditional Unix command-line
tool design. Journal data is stored in plain text and is
safe to inspect or process using standard Unix utilities.

.SH DESIGN
State-changing operations are implemented using atomic
file replacement to avoid partial writes or corrupted
journal states.

.SH EXAMPLES
Add a new entry:
.RS
jrnlc add "Finished N-body simulation draft"
.RE

Show the last 3 entries:
.RS
jrnlc show 3:
.RE

Create a backup:
.RS
jrnlc backup
.RE

